05953nam a22008295i 9780814724477DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1175629380  a97808147244777 a10.18574/nyu/9780814785942.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548057  a(OCoLC)898893052  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE185.97.R27bR46 2016 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a323.0922231 aKersten, Andrew E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReframing Randolph :bLabor, Black Freedom, and the Legacies of A. Philip Randolph /cClarence Lang, Andrew E. Kersten. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCulture, Labor, History ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- t1 A Reintroduction to Asa Philip Randolph -- t2 Researching Randolph -- t3 A. Philip Randolph -- t4 Keeping His Faith -- t5 Brotherhood Men and Singing Slackers -- t6 “The Spirit and Strategy of the United Front” -- t7 Organizing Gender -- t8 Beyond A. Philip Randolph -- t9 The “Void at the Center of the Story” -- t10 No Exit -- tSelect Bibliography -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAtone time, Asa Philip Randolph (1889-1979) was a household name. As president ofthe all-black Brotherhood of Sleeping Car Porters (BSCP), he was an embodimentof America’s multifaceted radical tradition, a leading spokesman for BlackAmerica, and a potent symbol of trade unionism and civil rights agitation fornearly half a century. But with the dissolution of the BSCP in the 1970s, theassaults waged against organized labor in the 1980s, and the overall silencingof labor history in U.S. popular discourse, he has been largely forgotten amonglarge segments of the general public before whom he once loomed so large.Historians, however, have not only continued to focus on Randolph himself, buthis role (either direct, or via his legacy) in a wide range of social,political, cultural, and even religious milieu and movements. The authors of Reframing Randolph have taken Randolph’s dusty portrait down fromthe wall to reexamine and reframe it, allowing scholars to regard him in new,and often competing, lights. This collection of essays gathers, for the veryfirst time, many genres of perspectives on Randolph. Featuring both establishedand emergent intellectual voices, this project seeks to avoid both hagiographyand blanket condemnation alike. The contributors represent the diverse waysthat historians have approached the importance of his long and complex careerin the main political, social, and cultural currents of twentieth-centuryAfrican American specifically, and twentieth-century U.S. history overall. Thecentral goal of Reframing Randolph isto achieve a combination of synthetic and critical reappraisal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American labor leadersvBiography. 0aAfrican AmericansvBiography. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rights workerszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aArnesen, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChateauvert, Melinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGellman, Erik S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkins, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolt Baker, Arlene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, William P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKersten, Andrew E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc